Furthermore, it is worth mentioning that surface functionalization by Na+ is helpful to conquer ACQ and favourable for the enhanced solid state cyan emission. To confirm the role of Na, two control experiments were carried out: one used citric acid and dithiourea as the starting materials, the other used the same starting materials but adding additional NaOH or Na2CO3 as Na sources. All samples were prepared by the same experiment condition (hydrothermally treated at 180 °C for 2 hrs), and the corresponding products were denoted as CDs-1, CDs-2 and CDs-3 respectively (Table 2
                        ). It is found that CDs-1 without Na+ ions can’t be freeze-dried into powder and only have weak blue emission in solid state, while solid CDs-2 and solid CDs-3 using NaOH or Na2CO3 as Na sources have similar emission to that of the solid CDs prepared by using trisodium citrate and dithiourea as starting materials (Fig. 6
                        ). FTIR spectrum has shown that the obtained CDs is partially functionalized by carboxylic sodium (COONa). The structure of the resultant functional group contains a negatively charged RCO2
                        – group and a positively charged metal Na ion, and hence is highly polar. The existence of plenty carboxyl may have effect of restraining π-π stacking interactions, resulting in the obtained CDs have bright and enhanced emission in solid state.
